    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nHi all,\nA couple of weeks ago I was trying to work out what the window ID of `0` does, having seen `vim.wo[0][0]` around  and by trial and error finding it to be the equivalent of `setlocal`.\nI presumed `0` stands for the current window, but I couldn't find it stated anywhere in help. Eventually using `:helpgrep` and with help from on Matrix, I found out that it's a sort of de facto standard (to the best of my understanding).\n`@taffir_` suggested I make an issue.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI think it should be explicitly stated in `:h vim.wo` that winid `0` stands for the current window, similar to what is said for bufnr, because it is (IMO) likely the first time new users (like myself) use window IDs.\n\n> Note: only {bufnr} with value `0` (the current buffer in the window) is\n> supported.\n\nOr maybe at `:h winid`? I'm not 100% sure it's a consistent rule.",
